Parliament did not support the amendment liberating Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal a section under the criminal code amendment that condemned opposition leader Yuliya Tymoshenko.
The amendment, which would have opened the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-prime minister, was rejected by MPs at second reading of a proposal to commute sentences for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for entering into an allegedly unfavorable contract with Russia to buy natural gas.
The sentence is not final, the appeal of the convicted person is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko calls the ruling a political vendetta against the regime, and suspicions of court bias have also triggered trial in the West.
The proposal to drop Section 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the ex-prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members in the vote.
It needed 226 votes to pass.
