Obese child's diet: not eating breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with 9 percent of schoolchildren overweight and 5 percent of children obese.
Meanwhile, obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the latest survey showed.
It shows once again how important the environment in which they grow up and the patterns in which they are surrounded are important for a person's healthy development.
For example, sausages appear on tables in obese children up to half as often as in families of normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of obese people had fried fries for dinner the day before research related to an awareness event called Obesity.
It is also not customary for fat families to play sports, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children said that their parents would find time to move actively at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of obesity is not a coincidence, supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 schoolchildren from 4th to 8th grades have participated in the project.
Proper eating and enough exercise in the family is one of the determining factors causing a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of respondents reported eating five times a day in breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," reads one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage in the evening
Experts point out that relative details, such as the regular time of family breakfasts, are also important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren' families have their free time for their beers at the same time.
In most families, everyone has their own free for a day.
And the worst was finding out that a tenth of households don't have a night's sleep at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy fries are much more commonly consumed in families of obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly play sports, their parents had a score of less than half - 15 percent.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own diet according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes there are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming," the final report of the survey states.
For lunch as the main dish, pasta won just above the poultry.
However, children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and lunchtime vegetable dishes is also low.
Inclination to health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In many cases, the control group of survey participants who filled out the questionnaire after the end of the obesity awareness lecture is no accident, there has been a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the project results state.
This was noticeable, for example, in sweet sodas, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children were also much more likely to tick poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire, limiting sweet foods and dumplings.
