Need for Speed: The Run is raced across America.
recension
The originally carefree ride turns into a routine morning trip on the shift due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
The ambition has largely been fulfilled, but it is of no use when no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, had high expectations before its release.
He promised that the years-old Need for Speed racing series would once again take a bit in a new direction, and from playable demonstrations it appeared to be a game that might not be just in numbers in the action racing genre.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages, in which the protagonist gets out of the car and runs on foot, will turn out.
However, as is customary with the NFS series, many are a little different than expected as a result.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for more or less several years.
So it's not really mistakes, but rather a manifestation of a kind of incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced into a story whose protagonist Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution is to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't feel for a moment that the game offers the same thing all the time.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to previous episodes of the series.
So it's nothing world-going.
But driving across deserts, autumn landscapes or high in snowy mountains feels visually very pleasant.
Moreover, the races are enhanced from time to time by some uncharacteristic element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well planted in a row.
There's only a few types, but it's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the desired number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up again (classic stopwatch fight) and then there is a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, the police get involved, which makes your whole effort even more unpleasant.
New are the passages outside the car.
It's more like interactive animations where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help them by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you would expect (perhaps only three in particular).
As a result, however, it is to the benefit of the cause, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above, it is one of the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model is following in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that it is certainly not a who knows what nowadays, but it cannot be said to be a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll need to look elsewhere.
But the more functional racing still suits the local driving model quite well, although we could find better with the competition.
So far, everything is in perfect order.
But problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the model is no longer very good.
We don't expect a game of this type to count complex deformities and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before hitting virtually any object, then I guess everything isn't quite right.
Typically, when overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you only lick each other lightly, but sometimes in an almost identical situation your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even just shred.
Thanks to the reboot system, it doesn't really matter, but it will make you feel better.
Reboots are designed so that if you smash or drive far off the track, the game will throw you back to the last stop point on the track.
But there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it is more of a tool in case something goes wrong than you can rely on them explicitly.
Sometimes restarts don't help either, they'll be solved only by the need to memorly learn the given section of the race.
The big ailing of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners need to be run in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit in them.
Other times, you will meet "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially bad in situations where you see the opponent passing easily between two oncoming cars in front of you, whereas when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around them or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you reach them, because it's "calculated" so that the situation always happened right under your nose.
Opponents have another advantage.
During the whole gameplay, you will come across several places where, again, regardless of time, you will always be overted by the same opponent in the same place.
It hit the most at the end of the game on a long bridge where you're driving on the wrong side of the road.
The adversary must get there in front of you at any cost.
When it's in front of you, it makes your visibility about oncoming cars worse, so at first you're going to get a couple of nice smashes.
One can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fueled, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably disgusts you quickly.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, gaming is fun and sometimes so action-packed that sometimes you literally can't keep track of where what's flying.
And it basically doesn't matter if it's due to the concept of 50 unique tracks, sorting races so that boredom doesn't stand a chance, or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to change cars during races.
You have to watch out for petrol stations by the roads, because that's where you can change your car, even though in the vast majority of cases you can make do with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, powerful American crashes on straight highways, and exotic supercars for technical riding, such as winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you earn not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for both challenges and story.
To get a higher level of driver, various objects are unlocked: from cars to backgrounds for the profile.
It is also again connected to the online autolog feature, which compares your achievements with other players and procures other community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the metro tunnel (so be it), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (so be it).
On the speedometer, the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (so be it) flash, and then a subway train crashes in from behind and scraps you uncompromisingly.
In the newsroom, we will probably have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought a bit when creating the game, or whether the authors think we are really such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is very pleasant in most cases and even great in a few cases.
It is so sad that in some of the more tense moments, the imageling decreases, in some cases quite tragically.
However, this applies especially to crashes with a larger number of participants, when smooth imaging would no longer be of any use to you.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to like the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog of a different country" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, someone will probably not buy the game easily.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so quite awkward.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS work in the last few years.
But this is how the game feels underdue.
I'm sure it's fun, but be prepared for bugs to spl be splplthing you in the eye with the power of the airport spotlight.
