How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recreation and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies overwhelmingly sold only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton) for holidays to the sea.
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime moved towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to queue overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" at the travel agency.
Still, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West.
By far the most common, however, Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages, which czechs took and this habit survives to this day.
Since 1989, czechs have experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of is that it was not possible for us, currently the most popular Croatia, to travel freely until 1989, as it was part of yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa requirements for neighbouring Western European countries were lifted, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, mainly to Vienna or Germany in Austria.
Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to visit there at least for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czechs' tours slept in tents in parks, because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of czechs' travels at this time was the delivery of their own food, canned food, salami, etc. in order to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally buy western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with it average salaries were rising, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare charter trips since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of bargaining for quantity discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first ever direct charter flight to exotica was taken from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters to warm faraway countries fly with Czech tourists every year, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Around 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled visas for Czech tourists, which made our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 on one foreign holiday, including the cost of their stay. CZK per person.
