Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book, Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a list of performers so long that you get dizzy.
One piece of advice on how to act at that point: Carefully rip this page out and bookmark it.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund's novel narrative, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - at moments when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "antihistorical work".
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather a "book about what it was like." It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the wartime experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives inger like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fates, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It corrects the notion that World War I was all about gruesome trench battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
In this book, the soldiers solve problems with the fact that bee nests fall on them, they have to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or they face the presence of tse-tse flies.
It's been a very moving read almost from the start.
War consumes people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts coming in the distance and you're a woman who's at home with her kids, do you run or stay?
Who's coming, actually?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," Mr. Englund noted, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are all taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
Descriptions of their lives may sound both frightening and engaging, but thanks to the inclusion of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with hardship and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Substitutes, substitutes everywhere."
