After this summer's tragedy, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting them wasn't really that hard," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently released report by the British research team on European digital populism.
Facebook's personal information supply is so extensive, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply use advertising on the site to identify with absolute accuracy the demographic they're looking for - something that marketing executives have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, and then they turned their attention to them and sent them advertisements. However, instead of inviting them into a newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they were invited to complete a questionnaire that raised questions about their level of education, relationship to violence, and optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without even having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not all that surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men, irritated by rising immigration rates.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen."
Demos' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health problems to social trends hiding status updates, posts on walls, and "Like" buttons pressed.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them provides three different data a day, making this social network literally an "information supernova" behind the development of many new research. The number of academic papers with the word Facebook in its name has risen to almost 800% from five years ago.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"In the old days, when you wanted to do a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to a side where you'd never be allowed to go," bartlett says.
"Facebook is breaking all of this down - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken facebook posts were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
"The problem can't be solved if you can't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, Co-Author of Dr. Moreno and Director of the Center for Children's Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, told the Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify children at risk that we would not otherwise have had a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes its users' data.
The site's information team has compiled statistics on the link between relationship statuses and St. Patrick's Day. Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010, and the nation's satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - internet freedom advocates have long said that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the page is following them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the page.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
