7 lessons from a lost interview with Steve Jobs in this week's movie
When Steve Jobs died on October 5, the opinions of people who compared him to Henry Ford began to emerge - and voted him his genius the Greatest Modern Inventor.
In a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that was dusted off for a special film heading to theaters this week, it will be for all Apple fans that his creative mind perfectly understood the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer and a self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedant organizer and a man who matched every little thing to the smallest detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer from "the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work... [but] there's still a long way to go between a great idea and an excellent final product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show The Triumph of Computer Fools, which dealt with the dawn of personal computers. During the filming, a unique, more than hour-long conversation took place.
By then, it had been ten years since Jobs was forced to leave Apple, and he had his hands full with his new computer company, NeXT, and he was impatient to see how the general public would embrace the Internet.
In the end, only a brief part of Cringely's entire interview was used in the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transport.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
This material, slightly edited, forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which heads to select cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is famous for his reluctance to give longer interviews, Jobs seems surprisingly excited to talk about his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And he's also proving to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during the interview, there will be a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when jobs can be seen thinking perfectly about the answer to be as concisive and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to light, when he seems impatient with Cringely's questions and drives him to get to more important issues and topics more quickly.
The interview was filmed before the pixar, iPod, or iPhone era, and features eerily prophetic thoughts as Jobs assesses what other companies are doing right and wrong, offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It's one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, whom we see here as an eager dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
It wasn't long before he started to put them into practice after he had expressed his ideas.
A quick summary of the seven scenes from Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"Over the years of business, I've always asked, "Why are you doing this? and the answer was always the same: Well, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, he never thinks deeply about business-related things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused about the way costs were recorded - they often started with the words "standard cost", the amount of which he could only think about. At that moment, he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine the cost of trade in no time.
How he made a mischied at the Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
A number of things have been written about the device in the past, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a pay phone and were transferred from one AT&T network to another during the call, using as many satellites as possible.
"We've been around the world at least half a dozen times, so when we shouted something into a pay phone, it came from the other phone at the door a minute later," Jobs laughs.
"We were young, and we found that we could build a thing on our own that could manage billions of dollars' worth of infrastructure around the world."
The two of us made a little thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I don't think Apple would ever have been created without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a prank he and Wozniak almost pulled off. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican and asked if they could speak to the Pope, posing as Henry Kissinger in the best possible way.
Gradually, increasingly senior members of the Catholic Church were summoned to talk to an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and it was only just before they woke up the Pope himself to the phone that the couple began to sip and put the phone down.
How he fell in love with technology (and phoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett's number in his phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute interview, Jobs already had a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"She influenced me incredibly. It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what such a company was and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a CRT monitor, and I immediately fell in love with it.
As a teenager, I went higher and higher at HP, hanging around that computer and starting to write programs for it.
How he invents innovation:
In several places, Jobs talks during the interview about how he invents new products on the fly.
Early in his career, when he set out to sell a couple of printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to put together a whole computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days at his disposal, during which he had to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
Later, when he was at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember fighting quite wildly... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] until I got tired of it, I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies are running out of breath:
Long before he led Apple's resurgence, Jobs prudently predicted that many industry leaders would fals in their vision and lose their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what's next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing are already in charge, so companies are dominated by people in charge of this, while the people in charge of their own products are out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that led the company to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could own literally the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger than it is, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
Instead of winning, however, they lost.
How he sees innovation as a form of art:
"There is still a long way to go between a great idea and an excellent final product... and as this great idea evolves, it changes and grows."
During that time, you'll learn a lot about him.
You have to accept a whole series of compromises - you simply do not force certain things to do electrons, glass, robots or factories.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind - different concepts - all the time and put them together...
In the end, it depends on taste - you try to think of the best things that mankind has ever created, and in a way you try to translate them into what you do yourself.
Picasso said good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I was never ashamed of the best ideas.
Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked in it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians and, by coincidence, the best computer experts in the world.
If it wasn't for computers and new technologies, they'd be able to do amazing things in completely different industries.
