How to recognize a lie
A glance at recent headlines suggests just how serious and pervasive lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy with allegations that he sexually harassed several women - both sides say the other is lying.
Administrators at Penn State University were charged with perjury when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught using a microphone to tell US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie was able to destroy entire careers and steer the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by posting information that was immediately refuted by unquestionable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misbusing his campaign funds to try to conceal his illegitimate affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that swucted around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
It's crawling with stories of cheating at school and college.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to look good in their own testimers.
Mentors, who should teach the opposite, send a message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many scams do we encounter?
Studies show that in a single day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers had been lie three times in the first 10 minutes of the first encounter in their lives.
Telling lies, or "recognizing lies," is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it is not a social game that is similar to, say, Charade, where one shouts, "I have you". Deception recognition is a serious science sector working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been dispeled.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they stutter, stutter, blush or swish.
But don't deduce that it's difficult to spot and expose liars.
A trained identifier of a lie can reveal the truth from a sentence structure, tiny facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a vast and evolving industry of lying recognition, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can help you greatly in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read others well, let them ease their vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "aimed at others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they tell tend to be "outrageous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
It's called "initial observation."
Thanks to him, he will have something to compare later findings with.
Notice the posture of the subject, his laughter, his work with his voice.
You should know if someone routinely taps their feet all the time so you don't wrongfully accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But think of it only as a warning sign, not as evidence of a lie.
People who tell a lie can stop moving the upper half of their body as they try to remember their made-up story, they can turn the tips of their shoes to the door, bend to the exit, significantly change their posture or show "relief after the conversation" - an exaggerated relieved respite and a change of position when confession is difficult behind them.
Interviewees often give a false signal that the interview is over, only to see what the relief will look like after it's over.
Also, see the subject's language.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once misstated and used the past time to claim that his murdered wife was alive, sparking a nationwide manhunt for her body.
Deceptive individuals can also express themselves aloorously: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or the difficult question will be repeated.
The most common verbal signs are very minor.
Someone can use a lot of "mitigating language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... From what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
We don't know much about the facts in such an answer, and it's often another warning sign.
There is no magic to expose every lie, but it is possible to acquire the skills with which to track down a lie.
With these skills, a person will have a better chance of not meeting some liar and cheater in their personal and professional.
