Climate adversity has hampered the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's reign, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell and with it the economy
2011 will go down in Sinaloa's economic history. This is the first year of Mario López Valdez's reign, which calls itself a government of change. This government has brought with it high expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been recorded and even the main indicators of economic development have declined.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the possibilities for growth in the state economy, and caused economic activity to decline by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historic decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares of cultivated land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partially damaged. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a steady increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the state's unemployment rate rose during the first three quarters. Between January and March, 55,053 sinaloa residents were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. Unemployment rose to 5.28% in the second quarter, and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise, reaching 6.19%, representing about 74,000 unemployed. Thus, compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed increased by 18,969 people.
Less liquidity
More factors are to the factor responsible for unemployment during the year in sinaloa. According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on steps taken at the level of public policy.
"We are seeing rising unemployment, which is linked to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints as a result of legislation passed by Congress to combat money laundering. It's not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn, invest, or use them for something," he stressed.
Stop migration
López Cervantes said that the demographic factor is also contributing to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of the difficult entry and also because even if they get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising," he said.
unreliability
The labour market analysis in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability prevailing in terms of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the state's employed people work without receiving benefits from the Social Security Administration.
Other features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory, salaries are the lowest in the whole country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in sinaloa state was 5,352 pesths by September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesets.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with a decline in economic activity and an increase in unemployment, 2011 also recorded the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in 10 years. According to the Treasury Department, foreign direct investment reached $630,697 between January and June, down 87.74% from $5,143,312 in the same period a year earlier.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government lists investments amounting to 17 280 million pesets per year. These investments were mainly directed at service undertakings.
debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the state government asked the state Congress in July to approve a 3 billion peso loan. This would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. By November, no gains in debt had been recorded in any sector of the state economy.
reaction
According to business representatives, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government highlighted the government's lack of management skills.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We must work hard to regain the land we have lost this year. In 2012, we must redouble our efforts, there was a lack of harmonisation of all of our efforts and, in particular, the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year had halted the state economy and curtailed its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was a slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore dynamism to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. That is why we are well below our expected forecasts at the end of the year," he said.
Redefine a mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed towards more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we see work being made. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important that all the material and human resources potential that Sinaloa has is mobilised," he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of setting out a vision for the future that would better manage the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, some progress has been made in the area of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term plan," he said.
He said the current administration has shown progress in public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that the work done here is visible and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
