Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet the Italian President tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face the crisis that is keeping the country on the brink of economic disaster and which has put the entire eurozone in danger.
The presidential palace issued a statement announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The framework is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which has sent the debt level to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package required by European leaders. This is the only way to restore Italy's hacked credibility.
There's a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry up. Due to market volatility, interest on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity exceeded the 7 percent threshold at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organization Confindustria, told reporters after the meeting with Monti: "We said that we would support this government very much".
We believe that this government is the last resort to get Italy out of this burning situation.
