"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, the center-right party's secretary, told reporters.
Support for the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliament's support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any impediment or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the push, warning that Monti's failure could be a disaster.
Monti opened negotiations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organizations.
The round of negotiations will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who made it possible to move very quickly in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline late last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond interest rates have returned to critical limits, responding to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is €1.8 trillion, would go beyond the current eurozone's current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite general projections that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms and then call early elections.
