I think part of it is because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs we play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
That's how the show is more interesting for us, which is why I think it's more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you will.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we were going to be in one big rock band and that we were going to stay in it for over 20 years. Sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we've been given and we're touched that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which all the greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement comes from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We're proud of it, and we're honored to be part of a seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We're lucky they're all our friends, and we're honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky to still be in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open musical paths that leave everyone sufficient freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame wasn't easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find your balance?
As we grew, it became increasingly difficult to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much as it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You mustn't get carried away by being famous rock stars. Neither of us ever really cared about that.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something spectacular in the beginning.
We existed as a band for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, we are still friends today with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started out in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at pictures, I remember Andy being incredible, the way I laughed with him. It's always been a pleasure working with him, laughing, talking about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
National band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as openers?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to think of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them, I could talk all night about bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though it's no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt slightly separate from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine bands that I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were formed at the same time. And if music is still that valid today, it's something great, because it's music worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very bleak, although they can sound positive.
At both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs that are deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose a family member or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make somme music.
Peru:
Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized tuesday in a public hospital, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his attending physician reported.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has had four ser operas and is currently under the control of doctors.
Rep. Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will undergo tests within three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases, where they should find out why he hurts and why he loses power in his lower extremities.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could receive a pardon on humanitarian grounds, but the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He under surgery four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst on his pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in his legs were added to these problems, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his rule.
Mujica visiting Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation led by Uruguay's President, José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. It aims to expand trade between the two nations and touch on the region's political issues.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit full of meetings with policy, trade and representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The programme was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political matters between the two countries", the Uruguayan Presidential Office posted on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the dispute with France, which occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy listed the South American country as a tax haven at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that would continue to remain as tax havens would be excluded from the international community. This statement provoked a negative opinion from Uruguay and a consultation with the Ambassador to that European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries. Since January this year, it has concluded an agreement with that Latin American country to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concreteize fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) "blacklist", which has countries that have not established all the required international standards of cooperation in the field of taxation.
From a commercial point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) concluded since 2004, which strengthened the exchange of goods between the two countries.
Bearded plumber runs in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for more than 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of villain Bowser, but he has never appeared in 3D before: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives in all stores around the world this month, has been created from the start to take advantage of all the characteristics offered by the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows you to play three-dimensional games without having to use glasses.
"Mario is a character who has to tell how stereosopia should work without glasses," said a Nintendo-specialized press worker in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during a video game presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game created specifically for this carrier", because until now successful films like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of already existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesman said that in addition to being a 3D image, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and smooth game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple", the task of which is to attract less skilled users.
Once you have overcome this level, you can embark on a "second round" at the levels of the game that are more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose real time between "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, it will be necessary to play in 3D in order to overcome various challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This new arrival of Super Mario in 3D also envisages the character returning to the portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo plays to the note of those who follow the saga and repeats the successful formula from previous episodes. It consists in the plumber of a bearded man having to go through dangerous mined platforms to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find news in movements, in the surroundings, in disguises and also among enemies, the "playful" Luigi will also appear.
Colom approves Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has taken steps to extradite former President Alfonso Portillo, who is to be held accountable in the United States for conspiring to launder $70 million.
This is the end of a process aimed at Guatemala's response to a request from a northern country that demands portillo's extradition so that it can sue him.
At the press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was in line with the independence of the judiciary and executive, and that he had in mind that the criminal court had already ordered extradition.
He assured that during his mandate he had not "interfered" with court decisions and allowed all extraditions that came to his desk.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both of them for drug trafficking.
Colom's move marks a step in the execution after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to lead the trial against the former president, who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited after his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and respect for human rights is guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzling $120 million from the Department of Defense during his presidency. This process preceded extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and brought the case back into play.
Trinijove helped 6,000 youngsters in a state of emergency
The organization was created to help children without education not to be on the fringes of society.
The balance of the first 25 years of the trinijove social support organisation is very important: 6 000 young people at risk of social exclusion have received help. For 25 years, the organization has been helping them overcome difficult situations.
