"The crisis is nothing new for this organization and for the work it does," he said.
A sewed-up house was evicted, where gigantic parties were held
Intruders have appropriated 11 of the 13 apartments in the balmes building, 51
12 occupiers left the house at noon yesterday without resisting
All indications are that the nightmare experienced by the neighbours at 51 Balmes Street is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they were illegally occupied at noon yesterday, where they organized gigantic parties that woke up neighbors. They left the building by court order and without the police having to intervene.
After the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a recurrence of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," the administrator said.
The occupiers, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took all the electrical and partially water equipment, in addition to painting the walls and leaving behind garbage of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held in the first three apartments, lasting up to two days and waking up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a disco, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that sales had fallen by 80% while the building was occupied.
The owner of the disco points out that the occupiers of the building were unfairly competing with her because they were selling drinks for 3 euros, whereas at the disco they cost 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment company had to respond to neighbors' lawsuits over noise. But the problems were caused not by the visitors to the disco, but by the inhabitants of the seizing house and especially those who participated in the parties held here, whose frequency and intensity have increased in recent weeks, according to the angry inhabitants of the neighborhood.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that they even agreed with the owner of the building and have been forgiving her rent for nine months.
The city police have also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbors about the situation in recent weeks.
Alberto Fernández Díaz, chairman of the PP's popular party group at city hall, demanded last week that "the building be evicted immediately to put an end to the problems of civic coexistence suffered by neighbors and the destruction of the area."
The Chairman of the People's Party explained that only one floor was taken before the summer, but in recent months the occupiers have reached all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them there have even been thefts.
In this respect, he added that "impunity must be put to an end and that it is consistent when it comes to acts against civil liability that have taken place in the building."
Yesterday, the city police also evacuated a building in the Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police arrived at building 35 on Mont-ral Street after being called by neighbors who saw four people enter the building.
All four were immediately apprehended.
Park or mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of the tendering process, which entails more than a controversy over fees
The city's 16-gate tender reopens the debate over the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, in its heyday, the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison to New York's Central Park.
After cmb disappeared in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona. The Catalan capital is one of the few that does not focus on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
Qualifying Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of Yogi the bear.
That was the position until September, when city hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, plays into the park's mind.
Either that, or someone's trying to place the gate in the field.
So there is only one question: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both in terms of purely organizational and reflection on the city, this issue becomes a central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It is already as hot a subject as when two members of this old caste of the chosen ones shake hands during a meeting in an elevator.
And it was this act that created one of the rare match-ups between what barcelona's three architects and senior university professors think.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure is justified.
According to Roldan, after the bay party issue began, "the "mountain side" must also be discussed, so that Ildefons Cerdo's speech on green apples was not completed.
"We must base our principles on the principle that barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "gateway to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not think of them "as entrances to the park, but rather as a demarcation of zones where it is possible to operate."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, classifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers."
The dangers arising from the "uncertainty posed today by the public place project" after the experience of the 1980s, which had "its swan singing" in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
"To define something is to take the next step", that is, basically to take it one step further.
"New urban planning and planning tools must be borne in mind, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause real disaster".
Looking more closely at the question, Modol believes that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered a park", but the Barcelona part cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "must not end up in the dump", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his committee to intervene in the project from the "first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of pass that allows architects to engage in the debate, but "doubts" that it should be this technical profile that will lead multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skill," he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the name to this game is complex, because collserolo's global vision is missing from the selection documents: "There have been 16 tenders that deal with all the mountain-sea, but there is no longitudinal study to look at the area and understand it as a whole".
This causes at least he to apply for all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, a single gate project may run into the concept and definition of the architect of the adjacent gate.
In his view, the town hall should guarantee that the zone immediately above Ronda de Dalt should provide a full-length equipment zone to ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
Casino has released Jonas Larrazábal, who will be released
After 72 days of imprisonment, legal agent Cadino Red pardoned mayor Monterrey's brother in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonás Larrazábal spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after casino red's legal agent granted him a pardon before the District's Second Criminal Court, which heard a racketeering case in which the mayor of Monterrey's brother was indicted.
After the Casino Royale assassination, Casino Red's owner, Sergio Gil García, posted a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonas was asked to pay an economic quota so that Monterrey City Hall would allow an illegal operation at a betting house.
After the public indictment, the State Prosecutor's Office began prosecuting the brother of the pan-Mayor. On September 2, he was detained and imprisoned for 30 days.
He was then transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo, the state capital, after four hours in front of Public Ministry Agent Number 3 for property crimes.
He remained at the site for the next 49 days after a second arrest order was issued and a Public Ministry agent refuted the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On 19 October, he was taken to Cadereyta Criminal Court on suspicion of extortion of casino red's owners with a sum of one and a half million peso. However, he remained in a medium-supervised prison for only a few hours because he had been threatened with death.
During the trial, the leaders allowed him to stay in the city cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigation, sufficient evidence had been gathered to prove Jonas's guilt. Evidence includes, for example, the payment of 1.5 million peso to casino representatives in exchange for a promise that the operation would be allowed.
This Monday, Casino Red's legal representative, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, appeared before Judge José Luis Pecino and asked for a pardon for the region's mayor's brother. As a result, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal hearing, the public ministry representative assigned to the court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the associates had decided to grant clemency. But the attorney made it clear that the name would remain secret.
On the basis of official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal. No complaint will be possible in the process against him. It is also not possible to claim compensation for damages or punishment.
After the trial of the legal representative around 3:50 p.m., the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Breton.
The court's secretary, Jorge Yanéz, arrived at the prison in San Nicolás de los Garza to announce that he had been granted an official pardon and his case had been adjourned to the archives.
He also announced that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident that killed Cabinet Secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people show that the helicopter landed directly on the ground at full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, said that before the plane took off, the pilot stated that climatic conditions allowed the flight.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings became entangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost its hull".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he stated that no parts were found on the ground following an investigation carried out in the impact area.
"The search revealed that parts of the aircraft were not in another location, so the aircraft hit land as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all passenger transport requirements.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The Secretary assured that the most important thing at the moment is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation can take several months or up to a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the time of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that this was a routine overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At the press conference, SCT Representative Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at takeoff, according to which the aircraft is advancing towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Routes selected:
It is likely that due to the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility all the way to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Impact location.
The coordinates of the impact and the helicopter's latest radar recording are consistent, and it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption to the flight trajectory prior to impact.
Dispersal of aircraft residues in a restricted area:
The information currently available to us allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A diagram of the dispersion of the aircraft's remains suggests that the helicopter was complete at the time of impact.
There was no record of fire or explosion.
No evidence was recorded at the scene of the accident to say that there had been an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show footage that is believed to have broken down along the route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several locations.
After careful searching around the accident, in an area larger than the area of the site, the remains of the helicopter were not found, reinforcing the assumption that the impact occurred while the helicopter was still in its entiree.
Mexican Institute of Health Insurance Launches Research into Gene That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research entitled "The Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents" will allow for results on overweight.
In a report, miguel cruz López, head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit at the National Medical Center Specialized Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, whether or not authorised to participate in the research, can also participate in the research. People can come to the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where tests will be carried out on minors from 8am.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexican State), and since October 8, this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East of the Mexican State).
Once data are collected from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors to Mexican children and young people, the thus preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the age of six and 14, with parental consent and supervision, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He clarified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglicerides, cholesterol, insulin are measured every Saturday, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health officials' concern about the alarming increase in baby weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had an increase in obesity of 77% and girls by 47%. There has also been a dramatic increase in overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which determines whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark color wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and precukrov states.
So far, the information is confidential, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in UNAM Asphalt
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at UNAM's Faculty of Ology, creates modified asphalt with polymers to create a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If paving were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at UNAM's School of Ology (FQ), who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt cobbles were adequate, there would be significant reductions in potholes, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture Technological Cause of Potholes, which he gave during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalt with polymers, which should create a mixture with similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce pothole formation.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules of large molecular weight called asphaltens, and others with low molecular weight called maltens. Together they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, warned a chemical engineering expert.
A scientist from the Faculty of Ology observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers there is an asphalt insert, formed by small stones drenched in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that makes up the erm is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to decompose well.
If it were modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, says the chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer called a shell, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also covered in asphalt, would be placed on the asphalt insert.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt liner and must ensure road friction.
Since as part of the paving it will be subjected to a heavy load, the shell must be of sufficient thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. Water, in particular, has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult to get out, causing all layers of pavement to soften and thus form potholes.
He explained that during the formation of potholes, the film of the shell is first damaged, and only then does the asphalt insert be damaged. However, damage does not occur at the same time, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must correspond to the load on vehicles and must be guaranteed that this load will not exceed. Only then can we prevent the frequent formation of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow easy repair of potholes without having to use high temperatures.
