Nord Stream, russia's new gas port of entry to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has begun to work.
It must supply gas equivalent to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration last Tuesday of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned the control wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network together.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will begin to flow into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Federal State of Mecklenburg-Pomerana.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be supplied, a quantity equal to all French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly objected to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being routed around the country by a third state (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, the two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pressing Russia by threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying that this is a politically sensitive subject.
Western Europe has gained greater certainty in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from east and west.
Barely five years ago, Russia succeeded in pushing through its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy, gas-rich Western states whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating the point at which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply points.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating back to World War II had to be avoided.
"For safety reasons, almost 100 had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a nord stream spokesman.
Measures to protect fauna and flora also needed to be increased.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like the 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere on its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but was rejected by project managers when the Swedes were little wanted to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settle off their coast.
"In the event of a fault, we will stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since the welds were designed to cause a leak once every 100,000 years.
An underwater robot pulled by a ship performs an inspection of the condition of the pipeline from the outside, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by equipment circulating inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the finish line, after a full three days of travel at 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains the leader, holding a 51% stake.
He was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream in charge of building and operating the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company all its gas transport capacity for five years under a contract that could be renewed.
"Gazprom will profit from total capacity, whatever the amount of real gas transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing of the construction of the pipeline was secured by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs thus increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be remedied, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coastline with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
