Why is the proportion of unemployed handicapped workers so high?
About 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
Today opens on 15. A week for employing the handicapped.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, ceo of Adapt, which organizes The Week for the Employment of the Handicapped."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of the unemployed was not two, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for unemployed disabled people, numerous obstacles remain before they start work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They are low-skilled: 80% do not have a high school diploma, and of the 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are handicapped.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the handicapped versus 38% on average.
In short, these are criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and which are at the heart of the problem, according to Christian Grapin, ceo of Tremplin, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
What remains is unspoken, ways of thinking that are surely evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association found that the managers interviewed had a "low level of knowledge about people with disabilities" with an exaggerated notion of people in wheelchairs and mental or mental shortcomings.
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still a long way from achieving the goal of employing 6% of the handicapped workers set out in the 1987 Law.
The most recent known figures, which date back to 2008, give a status equal to 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, ceo of Agefiph, an organization charged with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of 'fined' undertakings, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from €606 million to €480 million) between 2007 and 2011.
" The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put a lot of pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
